    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm working on an embedded c++ project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow memory leak. the system runs fine for a few hours but then eventually runs out of available ram and crashes. i don't see any obvious missing deletes in my main loop. how should i go about systematically finding where the leak is happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A memory leak in an embedded system, especially one running for hours, is a tricky beast. You'll need to track the memory allocation patterns, which is often harder than a standard desktop debugging session. I suggest using a memory profiling tool or, if that's too heavy for your resource-constrained environment, implementing custom memory tracking.\n\nFirst, you can wrap your `new` and `delete` operators (or `malloc`/`free` if you're using C-style allocation) to log every allocation and deallocation. This logging mechanism should record the size requested and the call stack trace where the allocation occurred. If you see an allocation that never has a corresponding deallocation, you've found your leak source. This is a systematic approach, though it requires some upfront coding effort.",
      "source": "target",
